               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-269-person1865">
                  SAMUEL 
                  BURCHFIELD
               <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1865" type="surname" value="BURCHFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1865" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1865" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18310407-269-viclabel1435" type="occupation">rope-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-269-victim1864 t18310407-269-viclabel1435"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18310407-269-crimeloc1436">Poplar</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-269-crimeloc1436" type="placeName" value="Poplar"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-269-crimeloc1436" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-269-off1433 t18310407-269-crimeloc1436"></join>; the prisoner was in my service. On the 3rd of April - the Policeman came to my house with a spoon, which I believe to be mine - I have brought one here, which corresponds with it - I understood from my servant<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183104070120"></xptr>that one was missing, but she is not here - the prisoner was in the habit of coming into the house at times - he had been two or three years in my employ.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-269-person1866">
                  WILLIAM 
                  REEVES
               <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1866" type="surname" value="REEVES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1866" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1866" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. On the 4th of April I was fetched to Mr. Young's - he gave the prisoner in charge, with this spoon - I asked how he came by it - he said he had been playing at buttons and marbles with some boys in Limehouse-causeway, and gave the buttons and marbles he had won of them, with 2d., for the spoon - he said he did not know the boys.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-269-person1867">
                  ROBERT 
                  YOUNG
               <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1867" type="surname" value="YOUNG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1867" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1867" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. On the 4th of April the prisoner came to my shop, and offered this spoon to pawn; I asked who he brought it from; he said from his mother - he gave several accounts about it, and at last I said, "I suppose you brought it from some boy?" - he said he did, and I gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-269-person1868">
                  SAMUEL 
                  BURCHFIELD
               <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1868" type="surname" value="BURCHFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1868" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-269-person1868" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My initials are on the spoon -I have one here marked the same way, and I believe it to be mine - I always found the prisoner honest.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I played with some boys, and won some marbles of them - they asked me to buy the spoon; I gave the marbles and 2d. for it.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 13. - <rs id="t18310407-269-verdict1437" type="verdictDescription">
